article.description: Theo Ratliff had 11 points, 11 rebounds and eight blocked shots to lead the Portland Trail Blazers to a 83-81 victory over the Sacramento Kings on Friday.
article.headline: Blazers remain in ninth place
article.linkText: Despite late surge to tie, Kings lose to Blazers
article.story:
PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Coach Maurice Cheeks had one word as he watched yet another of Theo Ratliff's dramatic blocks: "Unbelievable." Ratliff had 11 points, 11 rebounds and eight blocked shots to help Portland fend off the Sacramento Kings 83-81 Friday night. "That's my game," Ratliff said. "I just go all out like a maniac out there on the court, block shots, get in their heads, get them thinking about me." It was the Blazers' second straight victory after losing five of their previous six. Portland, trying to extend its streak of 21 consecutive playoff appearances, remained two games behind eighth-place Denver in the Western Conference playoff race. Damon Stoudamire had 20 points and Zach Randolph added 17 points and 14 rebounds. The Western Conference-leading Kings trailed by as many as 14 points but came back in the final quarter and tied it 75 on Anthony Peeler's 3-pointer with 5:56 left. Mike Bibby's layup with 2:02 left tied it again at 81 before Randolph hit a jumper and Ratliff blocked an attempt by Bibby. Doug Christie missed a 3-point attempt as time ran out. As streamers poured down on the Rose Garden court, Cheeks high-fived Stoudamire, while Derek Anderson and Ruben Patterson jumped onto the scorers table and raised their arms to a standing ovation from the sellout crowd. "The drama of that game was incredible and I think everybody got caught up in it," Cheeks said. "We knew Sacramento would make a run in the fourth and they did, but we hit some shots and held them off." The Kings got their fourth-quarter energy boost despite playing the second of back-to-back games. They beat Dallas 120-102 on Thursday night to briefly match Indiana for the league's best record. "It was an extraordinary effort by everybody," Ratliff said. "This team (Sacramento) puts up 120 points and last night we knew they were averaging 105 points. We wanted to keep them under 100. We did a great job playing defense, keeping this team to 81." Sacramento's Chris Webber had 16 points playing in his sixth game since he was activated from the injured list on Feb. 16. Peja Stojakovic had 18 points and nine rebounds for the Kings. Randolph was 0-for-6 from the floor before his jumper put the Blazers up 18-17 in the first quarter. The Blazers extended the lead to as many as eight points and were ahead 45-41 at the break. The Blazers took a 61-50 third-quarter lead when Ratliff blocked Stojakovic and Darius Miles took the ball downcourt for an alley-oop dunk. The move made Cheeks shout "Unbelievable!" Patterson's dunk following another block by Ratliff -- this one of Brad Miller -- put Portland up 67-53. "He went after everything," Sacramento coach Rick Adelman said of Ratliff. "You've got to give him credit: He challenged everything and altered a lot of shots." This season, Ratliff has blocked 229 shots for a league-best average of 3.37 per game. In 15 games as a Trail Blazer, he's averaging 4.2 a game.

Game notes
The Sacramento Kings signed guard Rodney Buford for the rest of the season Friday. Buford, a fourth-year pro playing for his fifth NBA team, is averaging 1.5 points in 13 games for the Kings. He made the Kings' roster out of training camp, but was cut after playing just six games. ... Randolph has 37 double-doubles this season. ... With the loss, Adelman remains one win shy of matching Les Harrison for the most coaching wins in franchise history (295).
